The surface chemical composition of the BiOCl/BiOBr obtained and the 5 wt% CQDs/BiOCl/BiOBr composite were determined by XPS spectroscopy (Fig. 2
                        ). In Fig. 2a, the survey scan XPS spectrum shows that the BiOCl/BiOBr and 5 wt% CQDs/BiOCl/BiOBr consist of Bi, C, O, Br and Cl. In the high-resolution spectrum (Fig. 2b), two strong peaks located at 164.6 and 159.2 eV can be ascribed to Bi 4f5/2 and Bi 4f7/2, indicating the Bi3+ in the crystal structure [17]. Compared to the Bi 4f peaks in the BiOCl/BiOBr sample, the Bi 4f peaks in the 5 wt% CQDs/BiOCl/BiOBr composite display a slight shift, implying that the chemical environment of surface Bi in 5 wt% CQDs/BiOCl/BiOBr composite has altered and may be attributed to the existence of a BiC interaction in 5 wt% CQDs/BiOCl/BiOBr composite [34]. The high-resolution XPS spectrum of Cl 2p shows two major peaks at approximately 198.5 and 197.1 eV, which can be due to the chloride ions (Cl−) (Fig. 2c) [35]. Furthermore, the featured peaks of Br 3d (Fig. 2d) at 70.1 and 69.1 eV, which correspond to Br 3d3/2 and Br 3d5/2 
                        [36]. The O 1s peak at 530.3 eV (Fig. 2e) can be attributed to the oxygen of the BiOCl/BiOBr material. In Fig. 2f, the high-resolution XPS spectra of C 1s displays the surface functional groups of CQDs. The strong peak at approximately 284.7 eV can be due to the CC bond with the sp2 orbital, and the peaks centered around 286.0 and 287.5 eV are assigned to the oxygenated carbon and nitrous carbon, respectively [37]. The results of XPS reveal the coexistence of BiOCl, BiOBr and CQDs in CQDs/BiOCl/BiOBr composites.
